The Ultimate Act of Parental Love: Granting Permission to Disengage!

A few days ago, I was speaking with my 14-year-old son and I initiated a conversation I wish more parents would have. I looked him in the eye and said:

"If I am ever toxic, hurtful or destructive in my behavior—if I gaslight you or refuse to be accountable—you have the right to call me out on it."

He laughed, saying he couldn't imagine me ever being "toxic." I pressed the point: “Who knows? What if, without realizing it, I become an emotionally unhealthy parent in the future?”

I told him this: If I deny his truth or refuse to genuinely change my bad behavior, his priority must be himself and his future family. He has the absolute right to distance himself and his family from me.

The Anti-Enmeshment Contract
This conversation is the ultimate anti-enmeshment contract. It is the core work of raising emotionally intelligent humans. It's a direct challenge to the generational expectation that parental loyalty must trump emotional well-being.

Our children are not our property!! They are not an extension of our egos. As Rudyard Kipling famously captured in his poem "The Children," they "come through you but not from you and though they are with you yet they belong not to you."

The true measure of our success as parents is not how attached they are to us, but how courageous and secure they are without us.

Empowering the Next Generation
By granting this permission now, we accomplish two vital things:

1. We Model Accountability: We show them that healthy adults, even parents, are fallible and that genuine self-reflection is the standard—not defensiveness. We normalize the idea that emotional growth is a lifelong journey.

2. We Arm Them Against Toxicity: We equip them with the language and the psychological permission to protect themselves. If they ever encounter a toxic family member (including their parents), they will have a foundation of self-worth that tells them: My peace is my priority.

This is the hardest, yet most loving, thing a parent can do: to plant the seed of independence so deep that, if necessary, they can choose their own well-being over a loyalty that harms them.

 I hope I never give him a reason to use this permission, but I will sleep better knowing he has it.

Be the change you wish to see !

What is the most uncomfortable, but necessary, conversation you have had with your children about emotional health?

Do share this with anyone who may benefit from this post.

Thank you ! 😊
